{"id":"2010.08217","submitter":"Hiroki Tanabe","authors":"Hiroki Tanabe, Ellen H. Fukuda, Nobuo Yamashita","title":"Convergence rates analysis of a multiobjective proximal gradient method","comments":"will appear in Optim. Lett","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s11590-022-01877-7","report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Many descent algorithms for multiobjective optimization have been developed\nin the last two decades. Tanabe et al. (Comput Optim Appl 72(2):339--361, 2019)\nproposed a proximal gradient method for multiobjective optimization, which can\nsolve multiobjective problems, whose objective function is the sum of a\ncontinuously differentiable function and a closed, proper, and convex one.\nUnder reasonable assumptions, it is known that the accumulation points of the\nsequences generated by this method are Pareto stationary. However, the\nconvergence rates were not established in that paper. Here, we show global\nconvergence rates for the multiobjective proximal gradient method, matching\nwhat is known in scalar optimization. More specifically, by using merit\nfunctions to measure the complexity, we present the convergence rates for\nnon-convex ($O(\\sqrt{1 / k})$), convex ($O(1 / k)$), and strongly convex\n($O(r^k)$ for some $r \\in (0, 1)$) problems. We also extend the so-called\nPolyak-{\\L}ojasiewicz (PL) inequality for multiobjective optimization and\nestablish the linear convergence rate for multiobjective problems that satisfy\nsuch inequalities ($O(r^k)$ for some $r \\in (0, 1)$).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 16 Oct 2020 08:00:12 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 16 Feb 2021 06:34:20 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 3 Aug 2021 01:17:34 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 28 Dec 2021 16:46:53 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Fri, 8 Apr 2022 07:22:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-11"}
